    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1219697400" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1219697400" />
    <a title="Michael" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9852281-michael"><img alt="Michael" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1338272291p2/9852281.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1219697400?book_show_action=true">Mar 05, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael" href="/user/show/9852281-michael">Michael</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1219697400" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16474084361714021186">Galeano starts off by reminding us this is a work of literature and not an anthology, and for this reason I&apos;m not entirely sure how to review it. Firstly, because I don&apos;t entirely trust translations of literature, and secondly because I don&apos;t believe Galeano. As a literary work, the first volume in the Memory of Fire trilogy is astounding - its gut-wrenching vignettes and spiritually cohesive yet stylistically diverse journey is late 20th century prose at its finest, but as an anthology and as a</span>
  <span id="freeText16474084361714021186" style="display:none">Galeano starts off by reminding us this is a work of literature and not an anthology, and for this reason I'm not entirely sure how to review it. Firstly, because I don't entirely trust translations of literature, and secondly because I don't believe Galeano. As a literary work, the first volume in the Memory of Fire trilogy is astounding - its gut-wrenching vignettes and spiritually cohesive yet stylistically diverse journey is late 20th century prose at its finest, but as an anthology and as a history of a people, it is supreme. Galeano has the unique and much envied ability to tell the whole story in a few words. As a researcher and cataloger, he proves himself to be among the best. Echoing the impressively researched Open Veins of Latin America, while adopting the self-admittedly superior prosaic character and succinctness of Days and Nights of Love and War, Galeano appears to have found his niche and built his opus. I'm yet to read the following two volumes, though soon will, but this one left me so excited I had to throw some words down.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16474084361714021186" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review1219697400">
  <td colspan="2">
    <div class="updateActionLinks">
        <a class="right flag" rel="nofollow" id="flag_link1219697400" title="Flag this review as inappropriate." href="/flagged/new?resource_id=1219697400&amp;resource_type=Review&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F264891.Genesis">flag</a>





